{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:10:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:10:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1323"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1323"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.62,0.03,0.19,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111532"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"702"},{"type":"tags","id":"8752"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111532"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn intern is called to the ward to review a 75-year-old man who has suddenly become unwell. The patient is day 1 post-left-sided mandibulectomy and extensive left neck flap reconstruction for an invasive squamous cell carcinoma. He appeared well on the morning ward round.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the intern approaches the bay, the nurse calls Code Blue and sounds the emergency bedside alarm. At the bedside, the doctor notices the patient is in distress, dyspnoeic and the left-sided neck flap has become swollen and engorged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe airway is patent. A Guedel airway is inserted immediately.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wait for the Code Blue team","Apply a non-rebreather mask with 15L/min oxygen","Investigate the obstruction with nasoendoscopy","Immediate transfer to theatre","Emergency cricothyroidotomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an obstructed airway as a complication of flap reconstruction. The most important initial step in management, as part of the primary survey is to apply \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen\u003C/strong\u003E via face mask. A bag and mask should also be available to provide supplementary ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical free flaps are the preferred method for reconstruction following resection of most head and neck cancers. The survival rate of a flap is around 95%, however it is associated with early complications including infection, ischaemia, bleeding and dehiscence. In these cases, oedema can lead to airway obstruction, which is life-threatening and requires prompt intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enasoendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be on benefit in this patient and should not delay resuscitation with oxygen. Emergent \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical intervention in theatre\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Ecricothyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E may be options to secure the airway for this patient, however the initial step should be resuscitation which will include high flow oxygen and securing IV access. There is no reason why basic resuscitation cannot be commenced while \u003Cstrong\u003Ewaiting for the CODE BLUE team.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oxygenation is the key initial step in managing a threatened airway"],"references":["Batuwitage B, Charters P. Postoperative management of the difficult airway. BJA Education. 2017;17(7):235-41.","Lynch J, Crawley SM. Management of airway obstruction. BJA Education. 2018;18(2):46-51.","McCarty JL, Corey AS, El-Deiry MW, Baddour HM, Cavazuti BM, Hudgins PA. Imaging of Surgical Free Flaps in Head and Neck Reconstruction. American Journal of Neuroradiology. 2019;40(1):5."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93618"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-15T14:51:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-15T14:51:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1323"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111532"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul